# MVC Calculator

A desktop calculator application built with **Java Swing**, demonstrating clean **MVC architecture** and core **design patterns** in object-oriented programming.
---

## Project Overview

This project implements a fully functional calculator with a modern dark-themed GUI. It serves as a practical study of how to structure a Swing application using the **Model-View-Controller** pattern, ensuring each layer is decoupled and independently testable.

### Key Features

- Six arithmetic operations: `+` `−` `×` `÷` `%` `^`
- Operator selection via `JComboBox` dropdown
- Real-time formula display with color-coded results (green for success, red for error)
- Input validation and graceful error handling (division by zero, invalid input)
- Placeholder text with focus-aware behavior
- Button hover effects
- Dark theme (Catppuccin Mocha-inspired palette)

---

## Architecture

```
┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                      Main                        │
│         (Bootstrap on EDT via invokeLater)        │
└──────┬──────────────┬───────────────┬────────────┘
       │              │               │
       ▼              ▼               ▼
 ┌──────────┐  ┌─────────────┐  ┌──────────────┐
 │  Model   │  │    View     │  │  Controller  │
 │          │  │             │  │              │
 │ Pure     │  │ JFrame +    │  │ Mediates     │
 │ business │  │ Swing       │  │ between      │
 │ logic    │  │ components  │  │ Model & View │
 └──────────┘  └─────────────┘  └──────────────┘
    no UI          no logic        coordinates
  dependency      dependency       both layers
```

### Layer Responsibilities

| Layer | Class | Role |
|-------|-------|------|
| **Model** | `CalculatorModel` | Pure arithmetic operations. Zero Swing imports. Independently unit-testable. |
| **View** | `CalculatorView` | UI layout, styling, and input collection. Exposes listener registration methods but never handles business logic. |
| **Controller** | `CalculatorController` | Reads input from View → invokes Model → pushes results back to View. The only class that references both layers. |
| **Entry Point** | `Main` | Bootstraps all three layers on the Event Dispatch Thread (EDT). |

---

## Design Patterns Applied

| Pattern | Location | Purpose |
|---------|----------|---------|
| **MVC** | Overall architecture | Separation of concerns across three layers |
| **Observer** | `View.addCalculateListener()` → `Controller` subscribes | View is unaware of its observers; Controller registers callbacks for UI events |
| **Mediator** | `CalculatorController` | Single coordination point between Model and View |
| **Factory Method** | `createStyledTextField()`, `createStyledButton()` | Encapsulates component creation with consistent styling |
| **SRP** | Each class | Model calculates; View renders; Controller coordinates |
| **OCP** | `CalculatorModel` | New operations require only a new method — existing code remains untouched |

---

## Project Structure

```
edu/calculatorSwingMVC/
├── Main.java                          # Entry point (EDT bootstrap)
├── model/
│   └── CalculatorModel.java           # Business logic (6 operations)
├── view/
│   └── CalculatorView.java            # Swing UI (dark theme, components)
└── controller/
    └── CalculatorController.java      # Event handling & data flow
```

---

## Tech Stack

| Category | Detail |
|----------|--------|
| Language | Java 17+ |
| GUI Framework | Swing (`javax.swing`) |
| Layout | `FlowLayout`, `BoxLayout`, compound panels |
| Threading | EDT-safe via `SwingUtilities.invokeLater()` |
| Build | Javac / IDE (IntelliJ IDEA recommended) |

---

## Getting Started

### Prerequisites

- JDK 17 or higher

### Compile & Run

```bash
# Compile all sources
javac -d out $(find edu -name "*.java")

# Launch the application
java -cp out edu.calculatorSwingMVC.Main
```

Alternatively, open the project in **IntelliJ IDEA** or **Eclipse** and run `Main.java` directly.

